                  <acquisition> <date/> <placeName ref=""/> <locus from="" to=""/>
                     <persName ref="" role=""/> <quote xml:lang=""/> <stamp/> <note xml:lang="en"><p>This manuscript was collected by Moses Wilhelm Shapira (1830–1884). He was
<lb/>                     a dealer of antiquities and manuscripts who sold his goods from a store in the
<lb/>                     Old City of Jerusalem. He is most known for the controversy over his purported
<lb/>                     scrolls of Deuteronomy and the fake Moabite pottery created among scholars; at
<lb/>                     the end of his life, he was publicly disgraced as a fraudster.</p><p> The
<lb/>                     sources of the manuscripts he sold are not clear. In <em>The Athenaeum</em> no.
<lb/>                     2855, dated July 15, 1882, Shapira declared that his sources preferred to
<lb/>                     remain anonymous. He claims to have traveled to Yemen to acquire some of his
<lb/>                     merchandise. Because of the similarity of Shapira’s manuscripts to those sold
<lb/>                     by Avraham Firkovitch to St. Petersburg, it has been argued that Shapira too
<lb/>                     acquired them from the Karaite synagogue in Cairo. (David Sklare, “A Guide to
<lb/>                     Collections of Karaite Manuscripts”, in *Karaite Judaism: A Guide to its
<lb/>                     History and Literary Sources*, ed. M. Polliack, Leiden: Brill, 2003,
<lb/>                     893–924 [896]; On the provenance of Shapira's manuscripts, see the introduction
<lb/>                     in R. Hoerning, <em>Six Karaite Manuscripts</em>, London, 1889, V.) Shapira
<lb/>                     prepared a catalog, now at Staatsbibliothek zu Berlin, Ms. or. fol. 1342, of
<lb/>                     the manuscripts he hoped to sell to institutional libraries. A transcription
<lb/>                     may be found in the “Heritage data” section.</p><p> Shapira sold it to the
<lb/>                     British Museum (now British Library), London, in 1877–83. Overall, the British
<lb/>                     Library owns some 200 Karaite manuscripts which can be traced back to Shapira.
<lb/>                     However, the volumes do not always align with Shapira's catalogue; the
<lb/>                     librarians of the 19th century rebound and combined incomplete and separate
<lb/>                     leafs into complete books.</p><p> Other libraries where Shapira manuscripts are
<lb/>                     housed today include: Staatsbibliothek zu Berlin and the Sutro Library at the
<lb/>                     California State Library, San Francisco.</p><p> </p></note> </acquisition>
